      "playtime_at_review": 879,
      "review_text": "[h1]Flashbang Simulator[/h1]\nIt's one of the easiest games ever made, until you get hit. When that happens, [b]the copious amount of screen shacking and light flashes is as disorienting as real stun grenades[/b]. You lose track of where your character is on the screen, if you should push up or jump first to go back to flying, and what friend you have currently \"equipped\". Needless to say, that's terrible during a boss fight. The battle wouldn't be lost after just one hit, but since that hit causes players to get disoriented and lose track of what's going on and what to do, they get hit a second, third time. [b]The game stun-locks the player[/b] rather than the enemy stun-locking the playable character. Both the screen shacking and the light flashes can't be disabled. Even if they could, what we would have in hand is still [b]a completely linear \"metroidvania\" with regular forced stealth sections[/b] (like one per chapter, I did three of them in ten hours of playtime before abandoning the game for the second time).",
      "timestamp_created": 1588069084
    },
    {
      "review_id": "220466203",
      "author_steamid": "76561199579258095",
      "voted_up": true,
      "votes_up": 1,
      "playtime_at_review": 626,
      "review_text": "What a magical game; it feels like you got sucked into one of the Ghibli movie worlds. The art and the design are among the best that I've seen in pixel art. It has an interesting story and world-building; the gameplay is fun, relaxing, and challenging at times, especially with the bosses.\nThe puzzle were easy and there wasn't a variety of enemies but but enough to not make bored. The boss fights are so good, except for the monkey—I hate that one. All in all, the game is amazing.",
      "timestamp_created": 1773283217
    },
